5-4cbc-9b77-9dfb9dcac56d,Enstar,,Institutional,6fb4a94b-5651-4f4d-83f6-787c85ba4652,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.420015,2026-03-12 09:42:25.420015,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Farid Alizadeh,farid@enstarcapital.com,\n0b713007-efcc-4bd9-b367-db5d2d40df9c,ERGO,,Institutional,609c128b-9480-4eb9-92e0-02ea7185dc2b,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.423255,2026-03-12 09:42:25.423255,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,James Jepson,jjepson@ergo-re.com,\n1ddb8c08-8a4e-409a-a645-1418ae8a4562,F&C Reit (BMO),,Institutional,d782ba77-6ad8-4455-8ab3-78e3e6b29886,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.438587,2026-03-12 09:42:25.438587,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Jo Wilkes,jwilkes@bmorep.com,\n739a5162-5dad-413c-8060-2d6e13a1a3be,Fabrix Capital,,Institutional,1df24e72-3085-4af6-9268-ebb74b5988e6,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.441866,2026-03-12 09:42:25.441866,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Fabrix Sustaainable Communities -\r\n•\tPGP/Patrizia Global Partners (formerly Sparinvest) is a funds business acquired by Patrizia in 2018 and based in Copenhagen. They manage five global real estate funds with capital commitments of approx. €2 billion, all invested with/via local operators. PGP has a separate investment team and 100% investment autonomy from the main Patrizia Immobilien business.\r\n•\tPGP completed their final close on a new European Sustainable Communities fund totalling €500m commitments, mainly from European pension funds. The strategy is led by Marleen Bikker-Bekkers out of the Amsterdam office. https://reactnews.com/article/patrizia-closes-e500m-european-social-housing-fund/\r\n•\tFabrix and PGP have formed a JV to invest in real estate in London, with the initial commitments for this vehicle to be funded from PGP’s latest fundraise, with an initial €125m earmarked for the JV. \r\n•\tThe JV is an impact vehicle and the target returns of the strategy are ESG-linked, with the headline goal to increase the supply of sustainable community infrastructure and affordable housing in London. Fabrix’s track record of community engagement, success at planning and expertise in both sustainable development and on-the-ground social impact meant we were natural partners for this strategy.\r\n•\tOur target purchases are where we can provide long-term investment into existing real-estate to improve and develop new assets of community value and residential space and improve the environmental performance.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Louis Duffield,louis.duffield@fabrixcap.com,\n2a16f17e-9677-49a0-822d-2a523a7f927c,Fairacre,,Institutional,c478c1c3-7348-4b32-8c1d-d612dc773511,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.448003,2026-03-12 09:42:25.448003,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Ben King,Benking@fairacreproperty.co.uk,\n6e05753b-622a-4305-9371-b17bb23ded0c,Fanssmore,,Institutional,bc025f90-7f45-487a-b254-229cc474ffe2,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.454146,2026-03-12 09:42:25.454146,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Gary Lam,gary.lam@fanssmore.com,\n2dd735fb-d252-4f5a-b585-25b5f8ab5323,Fidelity,,Institutional,c8c921a1-dafd-480e-a2c1-54a22f96a43d,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.457156,2026-03-12 09:42:25.457156,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Will Stoll,William.Stoll@fil.com,\nc0951e63-e08c-4ba9-83d9-ae79ae2cb4d7,Firefly Capital,,Institutional,5920b5fb-f4b8-4314-b17b-6eea414c37c7,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.463656,2026-03-12 09:42:25.463656,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,David Bearman,david.bearman@fireflycapital.com,\nfaf421d4-4d6b-402e-b89b-252e8d79eb12,First Urban,,Institutional,6c15484a-960e-4aeb-aa2c-4f8da59fb994,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.469916,2026-03-12 09:42:25.469916,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Ben Goldberg,bg@firsturban.co.uk,\n5dd4babb-156b-46cc-a9f5-4a5439f2114b,MCL Financial,,Institutional,00af04f2-64fb-4aa0-bb80-e2ef38a2a4ac,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.677093,2026-03-12 09:42:25.677093,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Michael Mang,michael.mang@mclfg.com,\nc203b29e-3e8f-4211-a7e7-8dd0fa090e16,McTaggart Family & Partners,,Institutional,a41fdcf3-cac5-4f0e-9c14-7e569da80e13,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.684,2026-03-12 09:42:25.684,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"03/02/2023\r\nMF&P is the co-investment management platform of Western Heritable.\r\nA long-established Family Office backed real estate private equity firm, Western Heritable focuses on adding value to real estate and creating core assets to be held for the long term.\r\nWestern Heritable will always be a significant equity investor in every transaction the platform undertakes and stand alongside co-investors.\r\nPrincipal commercial investment portfolios are in London and New York.\r\nWhole portfolio geared towards income generation but slightly further up the risk curve.\r\nUse debt / third party capital on deals – confirmed they use debt advisors on deals\r\nHistorically interested in resi:\r\nWhere they started (affordable development in Scotland)\r\nNo current strategy in resi, prefer operational real estate\r\nCo-Living – nearly invested in Mason & Fifth but decided against it (and are glad they didn’t)\r\nCurrent interests / requirements:\r\nKey strategy – hotels\r\nNot yet seen distress in the hotel market\r\nFully owner operated / owned portfolio – x4 in London (Victoria, Kensington, Covent Garden, Soho), x1 in Liverpool, x1 (under construction in Edinburgh), x1 in planning in Farringdon\r\nTotal portfolio = 600 keys\r\nAll assets were office buildings where they took planning risk as a way of boosting equity multiple\r\nLast year acquired a majority stake and operational responsibility for another hotel group = 400 keys\r\nTotal portfolio = 1,000 keys\r\nTarget is 2,500 keys in 5-10 years\r\nHotel in Covent Garden is #1 in the UK (EBITDA conversions of around 40%)\r\nHave a solid brand and needs scale (up to a point) – max 150 keys per asset as otherwise it begins to lose boutique / city centre feel\r\nIn conversations with another hotel group that they are looking to acquire\r\nEquity cheques can get big and don’t have the equity to do all of it\r\nTherefore potential to raise capital for large share transaction\r\nWould need the right term / deal etc\r\nKey strategy – self-storage\r\nCore strategy – v-a office buildings in London (Farringdon, St James’s) and spreading into Thames Valley (Basingstoke)\r\nNot currently looking to add to London office portfolio\r\nNew strategy - tired offices on business parks in reasonably affluent locations (currently have a holding in Fleet, looked at Leatherhead), with a view to demolishing a building sheds\r\nLike JVs and have done a lot of them - would often be the GP as they like control.\r\n\r\n23/11/23\r\nUpdate below from the McTaggarts:\r\n\r\nHotels\r\no\tFarringdon (incl. Long Lane) – originally they JV’d with the adjacent owner (GMS Estates?) for a 3-building refurb / redev. McTaggart have since changed their mind and are now going in for planning to a hotel conversion. Around 140 keys and McTaggart will operate under The Resident brand.\r\no\tThey have got their hands full on their hotel schemes, with a new opening in Edinburgh in the not too distant future. \r\no\tStrategy on pause for the next 6 months.\r\n•\tValue Add offices – they have teamed up with Hugo Denee (formerly of Stepstone, now at ‘Longstock Capital’) to carry out AM / DM work on offices in Basingstoke and Bristol.\r\no\tCanons House, Bristol - https://www.linkedin.com/posts/hugo-den%C3%A9e-b97a6825_bristol-bristolproperty-greenoffice-activity-7092130566082310146-d3fT/\r\no\tPlant, Basingstoke (formerly Mountbatten House) - https://www.plantinbasingstoke.com/\r\n•\tSelf storage\r\no\tLooking to grow out this strategy – they are after VP / short income offices in urban locations. The game plan is to grow a portfolio.\r\no\tThey like the idea of having co-work space within the self storage facility.\r\no\tSome cross-over with their offices strategy – they like markets like Guildford, Brighton, Leatherhead etc where the office market is faltering and resi conversion is unappealing (i.e. the office building may be on or near a business park / industrial estate).\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Jack McTaggart,jack@mactaggartfp.com,\n6420f4f9-5cd9-4a23-9a06-a4e33f8de972,Moorfield,,Institutional,73b7cbf1-3d1a-4505-88bd-27ef4f8f651f,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.690456,2026-03-12 09:42:25.690456,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Chris Perera,Chris.Perera@moorfield.com,\n3fa47ffd-25db-43ae-987a-d34cfb546bf7,Grosvenor,,Institutional,a90a6765-99aa-4526-b72b-fed2998899a9,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.507037,2026-03-12 09:42:25.507037,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"London, Manchester, Birmingham and Edinburgh\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Jason Smith,jason.smith@grosvenor.com,\n123c3008-29b2-4c46-9370-b7dd7410447f,Harbridge Capital,,Institutional,5f83a367-9a66-4a04-a86e-78cc0925c7ad,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.513464,2026-03-12 09:42:25.513464,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Andrew Holme,andrew@harbridgecap.com,\n283fd5cf-ea93-419c-ab03-1758b256817d,Henley IM,,Institutional,1a006ae5-0f54-4b65-b635-3798dab95bee,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.516346,2026-03-12 09:42:25.516346,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Tom Duff,tomduff@henleyim.com,\n044966f7-d898-4ae0-b67b-4bd27c77198e,Henry Boot,,Institutional,bf5be635-caab-4941-a39f-af9e0a608eab,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.519323,2026-03-12 09:42:25.519323,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Adrian Schofield,ASCHOFIELD@henryboot.co.uk,\n72e625cb-66bf-4d41-adec-865a504f522d,Hermes,,Institutional,b8df4dcc-ad01-4161-9b75-9cb71108bf07,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.522314,2026-03-12 09:42:25.522314,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,NEW CONTACT,Nicholas.jenkins@hermes-investment.com,\n77569a52-5769-4d01-96fc-d6ed97893e0c,Jaspar,,Institutional,4fe36eea-9872-4778-ac64-0f0a0ce4a205,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.577945,2026-03-12 09:42:25.577945,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Consented conversion opportunities of historical buildings to residential with planning. NB: can be listed. £1m - £6m\r\nConsented/Unconsented Permitted Development opportunities. £1m - £6m\r\nConsented Housed Scheme. Up to 20 units. £1m - £3m\r\nPrimarily London & South East location.\r\nCash Funds.\r\n \r\n\r\nThere is a separate commercial investment requirement for the pension fund for long dated, securely let assets with development/conversion potential at expiry. £500k - £5m.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Sam Stickler,sam@jaspargroup.co.uk,\n20876de1-1c5e-4919-b0ed-bf309b47ffc6,JP Morgan,,Institutional,cca6d225-da6f-4eff-bd43-c1014fa680f9,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.581168,2026-03-12 09:42:25.581168,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Paul Harris,paul.x.harris@jpmchase.com,\ne4f2be4d-941b-4105-bd3f-8830119f1a4d,Kames,,Institutional,ef146d10-a535-45c3-8d81-3ef78e1391ab,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.585111,2026-03-12 09:42:25.585111,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Philip Bach,philip.bach@kamescapital.com,\n60996c6a-8078-480c-8ed2-03df105ac32b,Keystone Capital,,Institutional,896bb73c-cdee-4b8a-9ac1-bf9de2d93dbf,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.591646,2026-03-12 09:42:25.591646,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Max James,max.james@keystonepartners.co.uk,\n47f0a8f2-7c47-4367-add4-57ed2dab213e,Kindale,,Institutional,88873447-c812-46ce-aef5-a8f9afe3ac9a,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.602797,2026-03-12 09:42:25.602797,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Harry Rands,h.rands@kindale.com,\n9c690a00-c083-4f51-8dcb-80635463ef3f,Landscope Christies,,Institutional,204d3403-dcb7-4655-b8e6-817157643931,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.608807,2026-03-12 09:42:25.608807,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Edward Chaing,edward.chiang@landscope-christies.com,\n8021ebc8-fefb-4476-91f8-d08e128bd7d6,Pelham,,Institutional,6161664f-3d1b-4323-a625-2cd268609d37,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.758322,2026-03-12 09:42:25.758322,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Charlie Richardson,Charlie.Richardson@pelhamassociates.com,\n6f1e0b5f-2426-457f-8398-330e1c1c07d1,Martin Jones (Soho House),,Institutional,b0695442-bd50-4cba-9906-aabcdefdc299,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.664842,2026-03-12 09:42:25.664842,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,Has gone to work for soho house - it’s the soho works guy who buys the buildings and puts them in.  They are looking for up to 30k sq ft in the west end to purchase so any ideas,,,Mar 2026,,,,,,\na99deb84-212e-4ac5-8c4c-09c7c2d84c31,Legal & General,,Institutional,a77113a7-ef4a-49f1-b6a2-2bfd89aa5325,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.61531,2026-03-12 09:42:25.61531,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"2/3/2023 \r\n\r\n•\tGeneral themes\r\no\tModernise - operational real estate (net zero), diversify, internationalise\r\n•\tBTR - 3,000 homes, 5,000 under construction (including Wandsworth)\r\n•\tAnnuity fund can invest into BTR\r\no\tAnnuity key fund on buy-side atm, freehold deals / income strips\r\n•\tIPIF - biggest owners of ML industrial besides Blackstone\r\n•\tL&G Managed Fund - biggest investor is Nest (Pension Scheme)\r\n•\tStill interested in beds and sheds\r\n•\tKeen to increase exposure to operational RE, such as hotels\r\n•\tPBSA (Direct Let) – L&G have long lets but not much short let\r\no\tAnnuity fund also considering this sector\r\n•\tPAIF (Matt Jarvis) - not buying for next few months due to redemptions\r\n•\tSimilar reqs across all funds\r\n•\tRemain big in urban regen\r\n•\tJV with Oxford Uni on Science Park and other assets in Oxford \r\n•\tSold £1bn, invested £850m last year - thinking it will be similar this year\r\n•\tAppetite to do Life Sciences directly (not always through Bruntwood[?])\r\n•\tLGIM - has a couple of offices in Europe and may be an area to grow further, but more of a focus on US (LGIM America)\r\n\r\nEdmonton feedback: retail element was too challenging for relevant funds.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Charles Tweddle,charles.tweddle@lgim.com,\ne3017056-4d86-463a-833b-65316aeaab81,London and Regional,,Institutional,06ad1bf2-6824-4d48-bd5e-535586e67356,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.62686,2026-03-12 09:42:25.62686,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Andrew Burns,aburns@lrp.co.uk,\ndd7f0ece-8344-4dd8-9d04-00c5d3d00e9f,London Metric,,Institutional,8a175c0f-afd3-4c17-8c8c-6c03cd8c3856,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.629999,2026-03-12 09:42:25.629999,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Will Evers,Will.Evers@londonmetric.com,\nb8e65df4-9550-4a9e-b2fd-ab68f0ea9f0e,Lothbury,,Institutional,06413d9a-4eee-47bb-a642-df15923c00f9,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.635869,2026-03-12 09:42:25.635869,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Ed Hockley,ed.hockley@lothburyim.com,\n2a16af54-5184-49d5-9799-2b8646e706c0,LXi REIT,,Institutional,84a5893e-f118-44e2-8c52-8c8b65372706,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.641012,2026-03-12 09:42:25.641012,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,John White,jw@lxireitadvisors.com,\n3b74f703-b336-4a3b-b706-8de80f944bc0,M&G Real Estate,,Institutional,e28da8f4-2e41-4614-8118-7a3dfa96b886,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.644224,2026-03-12 09:42:25.644224,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Kerry Williiams,kerry.williams@mandg.com,\nd99343ac-7778-427f-9ae1-e13541641859,M7,,Institutional,17010f65-e283-4738-990c-1caca41a7aaf,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.649321,2026-03-12 09:42:25.649321,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"The Monument Building, 11 Monument Street, London, EC3R 8AF\r\n\r\n•\tHis mandate covers all of Europe\r\n•\tThey remain acquisitive with Blackstone on sheds\r\n•\tAlso interested in retail warehousing and supermarkets \r\n•\tOW to send Morrisons in Brentford as they aren’t aware \r\n•\tNot interested in offices, high street, alternatives, shopping centres\r\n•\tGot the impression Kamco office acquisitions weren’t working out for them - @Jack Barratt let’s discuss \r\n•\tDid’t disclose pricing on Mailbox\",,,Mar 2026,,,,John Pow,john.pow@m7re.eu,\n391dc8ea-70b2-4bb0-96a9-10cd340286a3,Macquarie,,Institutional,5aa66816-b47f-4a95-a117-b63312262758,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.652452,2026-03-12 09:42:25.652452,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Tom Coleby,,\n74c48ceb-60bf-4ec9-89c0-83ff0cc61dfd,Maritime Capital,,Institutional,950a7c92-b3c1-4e7b-ae9e-66da213223c8,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.655598,2026-03-12 09:42:25.655598,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Max Hunter,max@maritimecapital.co.uk,\nd51c945f-6076-456f-b8f2-9395f2c69f32,Martin Group,,Institutional,25e21d3d-857c-4c50-9efe-f77c8603e505,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.658877,2026-03-12 09:42:25.658877,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Gary Martin,gmartin@martin-group.co.uk,\nc29afd39-2037-4198-84f8-0c5ff124fa7e,Martins Properties,,Institutional,c9296c2e-096f-40ea-8103-ddaefd49c547,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.667547,2026-03-12 09:42:25.667547,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Gary Sherwin,gary.sherwin@martins-properties.co.uk,\nfd592d4f-1fb3-4558-8393-53f341519bd9,Maya Capital,,Institutional,030c9f71-ba85-4304-8885-997d80bc9c85,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.671124,2026-03-12 09:42:25.671124,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Jared Hart,jh@maya-cap.com,\n5ee0cf44-b81e-48a6-b264-0bd9dcfbb5e1,Related IM,,Institutional,291e66b6-ec72-428c-b71b-0ea123587518,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.798575,2026-03-12 09:42:25.798575,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"09/04/2025\r\n•\tGenerally unlikely to do anything pre summer.\r\n•\tLooking for deals with a long lead-in time so that bosses in the US have enough screening time.\r\n•\tFirst few deals will need to be ‘safe’ given James is in a new role and wants to impress his new bosses.\r\n•\tWants 7% yield on cost, 5-7 year income with alternative use value, living sectors, fire risk, distress\r\n•\tBrixton – interested in staged payments and selling off MR. JB has sent.\r\n•\tBrighton – looks interesting but unlikely to be able to do anything on it due to timings.\r\n•\tOne Tower Bridge  – not interested.\r\n•\tNHGE – interested but restricted by timings.\r\n•\tLife Science REIT – wants to be put in touch with Farallon (Philippe).\r\n•\t£250-£350m to invest, PE from the US.\r\n•\tWill use debt.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,,,\n829f0400-aa22-4392-9ddc-292c2a63abe3,Picton,,Institutional,df27b4e8-b3ad-45e0-835c-4b1d47346481,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.764172,2026-03-12 09:42:25.764172,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Jay Cable,Jay.Cable@picton.co.uk,\n4bd754d5-86d4-477d-b000-59aba208060a,Prestigic,,Institutional,ecaa2c9e-1c2d-4eb5-9791-e0ac102c1547,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.773728,2026-03-12 09:42:25.773728,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Max Kinghorn,max@prestigic.co.uk,\n45bdec58-e4f4-44cc-b2d0-601f13532cba,Oryx,,Institutional,e5d340b0-7c89-4d05-924d-4cd5c5aa2562,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.745963,2026-03-12 09:42:25.745963,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Logistics development:\r\n\r\nStrategy: acquisition of land to speculatively develop small / mid box logistics units in urban locations.\r\nLocation: Golden Triangle, the Big 6 and the Southeast / London.\r\nLand size: up to 15 acres, depending on location e.g. smaller land size for Greater London and larger size for Golden Triangle.\r\nAll-in cost (acquisition plus capital expenditure): min – max of £16m - £35m.\r\nPlanning: consented or unconsented sites will be considered. Unconsented sites only considered if there is no material change of use.\r\nBuild: multi-unit or single unit to be considered.\r\n \r\n\r\nLong income:\r\n\r\nStrategy: acquisition of income generating assets, let to credit worthy tenants, on long leases.\r\nLocation: pan-UK with a preference for South East and Big 6.\r\nAcquisition price: £12m - £45m.\r\nAsset class: sector agnostic – offices remain challenging, but could work if the covenant, location, and tenant use are all satisfactory.\r\nNet initial yield: min. 7.50% (this is subject to change given market conditions).\r\nLease length: minimum 12 years unexpired lease term.\r\nRent review: annual or five yearly inflation linked rent reviews. Open market rent review leases can be considered, but at a higher NIY.\r\n \r\n\r\nOffice repositioning:\r\n\r\nStrategy: acquisition of office assets in strong occupational markets with the aim of adding value through capital expenditure and leasing.\r\nLocation: Central London, Greater London and South East.\r\nAcquisition price: £10m - £20m.\r\nAll-in cost (acquisition plus capital expenditure): max. £30m.\r\nCapital value: max. £750 psf. for Central London, max. £250 psf. for Greater London and South East.\r\nTenancy: multi-let or ability to be converted to multi-let property.\r\nLease length: max. unexpired average lease length of three years.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,,,\n1281ac00-ca92-4ef5-be52-db78c7eff95f,Orchard Street,,Institutional,1a984499-4988-4ba6-86f3-7112d4273593,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.726157,2026-03-12 09:42:25.726157,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"06/07/2023\r\n\r\n\tThis is our summary. Targeting 12%-15% IRR – we can leverage if it’s accretive. \r\n\tSummary for main sectors but we’re looking at care home repositioning, some garden centres and others so we’ll cover anything interesting. \r\n\t \r\n\tHigh level summary of the new OSIM SEIP investment requirement:\r\n\t\t· Sector agnostic\r\n\t\t· UK-wide requirement (although likely to larger or well-established urban centres)\r\n\t\t· c. £5m - £20m lot sizes on entry with heavy capex requirement\r\n\t\t· Short income (< 3 years) or Vacant Possession opportunities to ensure repositioning business plan can be executed \r\n\t\t· Preference to refurbish and add to the existing real estate rather than full demolition\r\n\t\r\n\tIndustrial/Logistics\r\n\t\t- Location: Edge of strong urban centres\r\n\t\t- Age: Typical 1980s/1990s sheds in need of heavy refurbishment but fundamentally decent kit\r\n\t\t- Single let: 50,000-100,000 sq ft / Good eaves / Decent yards required\r\n\t\t- Multi-let: Requirement to refurbish half the space within 2-3 years, leases outside the 54 Act\r\n\t \r\n\tRetail Warehouses\r\n\t\t- Location: In urban centres with limited competition \r\n\t\t- Age: Up to early 2000’s which require meaningful capex \r\n\t\t- Single let: VP or short income opps where the tenant is leaving or we can engage them to refurbish unit\r\n\t\t- Multi-let: Requirement to refurbish/’green up’ half the space within 3-4 yrs\r\n\t\t- VP: Preference for leases outside the 54 Act but can be inside where we can engage with tenants through existing relationships\r\n\t \r\n\tOffices\r\n\t\t- Location: Big 6 / Growth locations e.g. Brighton\r\n\t\t- Quality: Broken buildings in need of full refurbishment with fundamentally good bones; floor to ceiling\r\n\t\t- Planning: Upside from adding massing and roof terraces.\r\nNeed for VP within 2-3 years\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Harry Buxton,hbuxton@orchard-street.co.uk,\ncae60e66-98b9-4a98-9406-ae03d3a2a896,PIC,,Institutional,177e1bd8-9135-401e-b2e6-8f30eee81bad,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.761237,2026-03-12 09:42:25.761237,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"15/11/2024\r\nPIC Overview and Investment Approach\r\n•\tPIC specialises in managing defined benefit pension liabilities.\r\n•\tTheir preferred deal structure combines debt and equity. For example, in Build-to-Rent (BTR) schemes, they often allocate 50% as pension fund debt (e.g., from BP Pension Fund) and the remainder as IRR-driven shareholder equity, typically sourced from sovereign wealth capital from Kuwait. These investments target a 10–20 year horizon, with exits via recap or sale.\r\n\r\nInvestment Criteria\r\n•\tSectors: Long income, living, and industrial.\r\n•\tMinimum lot size: £15m.\r\n•\tLong-income investments must be investment-grade and linked to CPI/RPI.\r\n•\tPIC values a long lead-in time for deal preparation and execution.\r\n\r\nPotential Deal Opportunities\r\n•\tDavid Lloyd forward fundings\r\n•\tQ Park Mailbox\r\n•\tBrixton wrapper\r\n\r\nPIC’s Key Projects\r\n1 Ruskin Square, Croydon\r\n•\t£268m forward purchase of a Grade A office building leased to the Government Property Agency, targeting sustainability standards like BREEAM \"\"Outstanding.\"\"\r\nNew Vic, Manchester\r\n•\t£130m BTR development near Manchester Victoria Station, featuring 520 apartments, commercial space, and resident amenities. \r\nMilton Keynes (Bowback House)\r\n•\t£80m BTR project with 306 apartments, including 43 affordable units. The development prioritises sustainability with features like solar panels and air-source heat pumps.\r\nOctopus Real Estate\r\n•\tKey initiatives include the \"\"Senior Living Investment Partners\"\" JV, developing retirement living communities such as the St Albans scheme.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,,,\n8559d18d-70c3-4e91-962c-606205301926,Quadrant,,Institutional,5990cc59-b5e6-47cf-ad66-55bde3f16eeb,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.780252,2026-03-12 09:42:25.780252,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"27/01/2025\r\nKey Points:\r\n1.\tReviewing REX with a Private European Capital Partner \r\no\tQuadrant is evaluating the REX, targeting a partnership with private European capital. \r\n\r\n2.\tAcquisition of 6 Gracechurch Street\r\no\tAcquired last year as the first asset under a new investment mandate with FarGlory, a Singaporean-based, Taiwanese institutional investor.\r\no\tStrategy: Focus on core/core+ assets, indicating a preference for stable, income-producing properties with potential for long-term value appreciation.\r\no\tTarget investment size within the mandate is £50-60 million per asset.\r\no\thttps://www.quadrantestates.com/news/quadrant-and-singapore-based-investment-partner-purchase-city-london-office-uss?utm_source=chatgpt.com\r\n\r\n3.\tTottenham Court Road (TCR) Block – LandSec Disposal\r\no\tQuadrant, in partnership with AshbyCapital, submitted a bid in the £40m range for this asset.\r\no\tAshbyCapital was highlighted as achieving £100 per sq ft rents in their office schemes located opposite the site.\r\no\tQuadrant’s proposed business plan for the site was to pursue a full redevelopment or refurbishment, contingent upon securing VP.\r\no\tAction: Jack to send over the proposed business plan for TCR, subject to agreement on the fee position.\r\n\r\n4.\t1 Wood Street\r\no\tPotential interest flagged under two distinct capital mandates:\r\n\tInsurance-backed mandate: Seeking core/core+ opportunities, targeting stable, long-term income streams. \r\n\tSingaporean family office capital: A more opportunistic, potentially value-add approach with greater flexibility in asset repositioning.\r\n\r\n5.\tCanary Wharf Investments with Oaktree\r\no\tQuadrant has partnered with Oaktree Capital, having completed acquisitions in Canary Wharf.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,,,\ncba8c482-a855-41dc-a6c2-f247b07560cb,Private,,Institutional,fad0b141-71e7-4cf5-a8cb-c2093e014aa1,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.776745,2026-03-12 09:42:25.776745,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,Up to £2m,,,Mar 2026,,,,George Delligianas,george.deligiannis@gmail.com,\n1b170a00-ff0e-46e9-ad13-badb61ee5ad6,RE Capital,,Institutional,e8a7fc24-f431-4fa8-9c29-fa26e4ceaeb0,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.784172,2026-03-12 09:42:25.784172,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Ben Robinson,ben@recapital.com,\na2618ba8-70fd-44e5-8b60-cc5d68c8f5bb,Redevco,,Institutional,f8e32249-1c03-4193-8286-05064491b05b,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.789593,2026-03-12 09:42:25.789593,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Tom Hoye,tom.hoye@redevco.com,\n5352a77b-c56e-4d6f-8f09-8602531cdba4,REI PLC,,Institutional,694441bd-14c2-425e-9159-d8ddb1aeac84,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.792964,2026-03-12 09:42:25.792964,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,Birminghim high yielding,,,Mar 2026,,,,Andrew Osbourne,andrew@reiplc.com,\neaf5acbb-c872-46c3-bab2-b54ea696ecfb,Revcap,,Institutional,99bb7e91-bf58-4f9b-9a23-906cd8409846,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.801783,2026-03-12 09:42:25.801783,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"10/05/2023:\r\n1) Mainly on the opportunistic side of the business\r\no\tHappy in £2-15m, £5-8m sweet spot\r\no\tAlways in JV, 10% co-invest, in practice closer to 25%\r\no\tMin 50%\r\no\tJoint control decision making \r\no\tAgree business plan upfront\r\no\tRaising fund 6 - launched in Jan last year, Fund 6 - BA PF was cornerstone, now gone to Blackrock so trying to find alternative, Fund 1-5 been deployed / exited / some still active (fund 5)\r\no\t2-3 interested 'recovery capital' sources\r\no\t55-60% debt\r\no\tFocus on UK and Europe\r\no\tReturns with +18-20% IRRs\r\no\t3-5 year hold\r\no\tPrefer smaller deals - equity ticket ranges from £2-£20m\r\n\r\n2) Core Plus ME Money - looking for distrubution yield \r\no\tLonger term capital (5-7 years)\r\no\tFocus on Europe\r\no\t£1bn investments - some offices\r\no\tLarger lot sizes - £30m, some 50-100m\r\no\t11-12% IRRo\r\no\t+7% cash on cash\r\n\r\n3) Platforms \r\no\tUS and ME money - operational businesses\r\no\t5 deals so far\r\no\tProvide working capital money, and buying assets, trying to create some enterprise value\r\no\tSector agnostic - senior / social in Ireland, French developer, logistics pan-euro\r\no\t15-16%\r\no\tLeverage case by case\r\n•\tPlatforms Fund\r\no\tMiddle Eastern and US investors\r\no\tLook to buy and / or work with opco – grow platform from £0 to £100-200m, or buy into existing platform\r\no\t2 resi platforms (hence why they feel they are full on resi)\r\n\tX1 single family housing platform in the North of England\r\n\tX1 Irish strategic land play with a view to exit via forward funds \r\no\tx1 office JV with stake in the opco\r\no\tHave looked at film studios and dark kitchens\r\no\tNot keen on development\r\no\tGenerally, platform fund not looking to invest atm\r\n\r\nRetail and Regional offices\r\nLondon based PE fund. Involved in £7bn real estate transactions\r\nResi: favour BTR rather than BTS\r\n\r\n3) General discussion\r\no\tOwn petrol station business, in data centres, private schools, advertising hoarding, glamping business – like ‘weird and wonderful’ deals\r\no\tOwn stake in PiLabs (GP)\r\no\tLondon head office, Paris, Frankfurt, Stockport, Madrid\r\no\tBuild to sell = require a 1.5x equity multiple\r\n\r\n•\tDebt\r\no\tCurrently raising a new fund        \r\no\tLooking at ‘rescue capital’ / funding gap – mezz / pref equity\r\no\tWill go as high as 75-80% LTV.\r\no\tTarget 15% IRR.\r\no\tWill take development risk, although at a lower leverage.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Iestyn Llewellyn-Smith,\"Illewellyn-smith@revcap.co.uk,\",\n82089683-10a9-4d5a-9fa7-7c80cd3b363f,Royal London,,Institutional,12b5559b-f405-4379-94a1-785c3b3f7c58,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.805091,2026-03-12 09:42:25.805091,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Michael Lawrence,Michael.Lawrence@rlam.co.uk,\n5c0492c9-5048-4ccb-9fac-31336de3b8d4,Savills IM,,Insti