m.com,\n93765b4a-e848-438f-8a30-852637590668,Synergy,,Institutional,00ac4faf-b112-42cf-a377-1aec4359cc48,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.862298,2026-03-12 09:42:25.862298,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Sam,sam@synergy.org.uk',\n3bd09d1c-587b-4d01-aaa7-fa968c9e7e85,Taylor Wimpey,,Institutional,4f79980f-33c4-4dcd-85e3-ccc23dab0131,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.864905,2026-03-12 09:42:25.864905,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Alex Greaves,alex.greaves@taylorwimpey.com,\n1b108197-d2df-4179-ba82-f67e16dae769,Tesco Pension Fund,,Institutional,47d2a00e-3d69-42a4-b16d-467fcacd4363,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.874122,2026-03-12 09:42:25.874122,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,David Russel Smith,david.russell-smith@uk.tesco.com,\n8bf721e5-7dd5-4286-8297-ec28e64cb41d,Thackery Estates,,Institutional,6bae2d11-2b9e-409a-bdae-52dfa9b8d400,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.880312,2026-03-12 09:42:25.880312,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Charles Thompson,charlest@thackeray-estates.co.uk,\n87fc735f-f2a3-4151-9f6d-4857dfff89d9,Thor Equities,,Institutional,f535465a-fddb-4eff-91b9-b96cff929d59,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.883305,2026-03-12 09:42:25.883305,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Toby Cooper,tcooper@thorequities.com,\n7d832101-62e7-4341-9ba7-3208634942cf,Threadneedle,,Institutional,6cd88881-31a3-4b65-9bea-075710ffce56,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.886321,2026-03-12 09:42:25.886321,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"July 2023 (Jenny): Aegon we intend to reposition the portfolio over the next couple of months disinvesting from the sectors which we feel won’t provide growth going forward, the majority of the high street retail is being dealt with via Graham Fawcett if you want to reach out to him if you have any ideas and the smaller secondary offices Max is reviewing at Kimmre. Backstop will be auction for most if not sold by YE. On the acq side we are on the hunt for industrial, retail warehousing and student accommodation. PBSA we don’t have are own operator but after direct let schemes. Forward fundings are tricky as we are income driven and don’t want our cash committed – up and built best for us on a focus of good russell group unis and good quality accommodation  \r\n\r\nMay 2023: Columbia Threadneedle Investments has formed a strategic real estate partnership with Aegon UK. The mandate, a commercial real estate portfolio valued in excess of €568.6m (£500m), will be managed by Columbia Threadneedle’s UK real estate team. The mandate will be led by Jenny Hewitt, Portfolio Manager, and James Coke, Co-Head Institutional Real Estate, supported by the 120 strong UK real estate team.\r\n\r\nTREN AND TPUT main funds, pension funds only, £2.3bn last year and £1.7bn this year - driven by DB clients and valuation falls \r\nWorking out how to plug gap that will be left by DB funds\r\nTREN been selling significantly but no longer have redemptions \r\nLooking to increase cash in fund \r\nInvestment managers going through seismic change on this front (end of DB schemes)\r\n\r\nPE - \r\nRaising selected funds 1,2, 3 and select fund 4\r\n\"\"we raise funds like this when we think there will be dislocation / stress\"\"\r\nPreffered sectors are retail warehousing (specific underwriting model) multi-let industrial, strategic land \r\nDelivered mid teen net IRRs\r\nBearish on offices due to UK working patterns \r\nMoney raised 1st asset u/o, 4 year period, 12-15% geared IRRs, 505% LTV, 5.5% all in debt cost\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Nathan Hargreaves,nathan.hargreaves@columbiathreadneedle.com,\nfef69811-78d5-4457-81c1-dad9d6ede636,Tonsley Investments,,Institutional,674411bd-a5be-4759-9bad-58ff2faa6814,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.900532,2026-03-12 09:42:25.900532,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,£1-3m 2+ units,,,Mar 2026,,,,James Dodwell,jdodwell@tonsleyinvestments.co.uk,\n4c2a8931-af47-47dc-bce4-06066fd53ce8,Topland,,Institutional,72eb9c01-48ce-4b0f-8657-d9caf0edd890,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.90392,2026-03-12 09:42:25.90392,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Mark Kingston,markk@topland.co.uk,\nd23887d2-a7c6-4f78-89f7-f2dce87a79b8,Tribeca,,Institutional,fd5e3f7b-932c-4700-a6bf-bab80495ba54,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.907347,2026-03-12 09:42:25.907347,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Ashley Marrison,Ashley@tribecaholdings.com,\nbc674c68-7ec6-4ceb-ab13-268e7007071d,UBS AM,,Institutional,9b3b9f7c-c7ca-4fa8-b763-63ebb01dfb83,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.913646,2026-03-12 09:42:25.913646,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Joe Armes,Joe.armes@ubs.com,\n737c9e5e-fccc-4d42-b9af-8d48ad45702d,Union Investment,,Institutional,5d4a9fb2-1667-4b6f-947b-8c4c25d28eb9,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.916875,2026-03-12 09:42:25.916875,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Miles Skinner,,\n05a5bc00-12ae-4703-b0f0-2e4ccc09cafe,Capreon,,Institutional,4ef24dfe-9c43-431a-bb8d-4b76fa703ac1,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.219104,2026-03-12 09:42:25.219104,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Daniel Hall,dhall@capreon.co.uk,\n2bb3b869-3ae7-444c-a886-e1b2dce6e301,XLB,,Institutional,668fbd8c-98b4-497f-ae9a-b7fc3afa9b71,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.970763,2026-03-12 09:42:25.970763,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"06/11/2024\r\nTarget Locations:\r\n•\tKey “cluster” cities with strong CBD/infrastructure, such as Oxford, Cambridge, Manchester, Bristol, Birmingham, Brighton, Southampton, and Milton Keynes.\r\n•\tInterested in London but may face pricing challenges.\r\n\r\nTarget Sectors:\r\n•\tBusiness Parks and City Centre Offices\r\n•\tIndustrial, Self-Storage, Life Sciences\r\n\r\nAsset Profile:\r\n•\tFocus on properties that are vacant or with short income, providing opportunities to add value in the short to medium term, as well as land development potential.\r\n\r\nProject Specifications:\r\n•\tHigh-spec builds to attract skilled labour.\r\n•\tPreference for offices with green space to complement build quality.\r\n\r\nCapabilities:\r\n•\tAsset and Development Management (new builds and refurbishments)\r\n•\tMaster Planning (a growing area for them)\r\n•\tCapital Raising\r\n\r\nCurrent Mandates:\r\n•\tCurrently handling 8 mandates, backed by capital from AIMCO, Bridges, Pictet, Tristan, and KFIM, targeting IRRs of +15%.\r\n\r\nExample Projects:\r\n•\tSept 2024: Acquisition of Cody Technology Park, Farnborough (£112M) with Tristan Capital Partners in a sale-and-leaseback from QinetiQ.\r\n•\tApr 2022: Surrey acquisition with Bridges Fund Management for a 90,000 sq ft logistics development.\r\n•\tNov 2020: “The Powerhouse Portfolio” in Manchester with Pictet; refurbishment and ESG-focused management.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,,,\naedb9a55-8919-46ff-a3d3-dfb31dd4ef56,ACAI Group,,Institutional,3bfb28d2-6e0b-4c5e-9134-4dfbaa5f7bbf,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.083952,2026-03-12 09:42:25.083952,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Peter Dee Shapland,peter.deeshapland@oandh.com,\nf37e5dda-8be2-452f-8e49-08ec41204e59,AIG,,Institutional,1030a18f-a69d-46a9-a3fc-35dd82b9bb4f,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.093498,2026-03-12 09:42:25.093498,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Working slowly across the range at present, very BTR focused.\r\n\r\n*Core-Plus\r\n•\tCautiously working up core-plus capital but they are not quite there yet.\r\n•\tLikely to be later in the year if / when this is materialised.\r\n\r\n**Co-Living\r\n•\tLewis is focussed on UK and Ireland, but generally speaking they will look at co-living.\r\n•\tPrefer smaller lot sizes.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Lewis Mottram,lewis.mottram@aig.com,\n713d95da-acff-4311-85b3-4eeaf57ca062,Gascyone Holdings,,Institutional,e2641bcc-1860-4495-a14b-f981680d6a45,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.488508,2026-03-12 09:42:25.488508,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Adam Wiles,a.wiles@gascoyneholdings.co.uk,\n99f4f944-e70a-48ba-9ca7-ee5e1066fa4a,Vectis,,Institutional,b9b65001-17e6-43f4-9fe5-b9a09fdd4312,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.927468,2026-03-12 09:42:25.927468,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,£1 m London + Resi in tact,,,Mar 2026,,,,Chris Rayner,,\n40451a78-50a4-4b32-a0af-e4dcc87f6bc3,Watkin Jones,,Institutional,38207eb7-e9d9-429a-8d89-b12213642c61,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.93274,2026-03-12 09:42:25.93274,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Auug 23 -  \r\n\t· WJ are looking to increase cash on their balance sheet due to share price performance.\r\n\t\t\to They are exiting sites that they have purchase options over (e.g. sites they have bought STP). \r\n\t\t\to They are also potentially looking to exit sites where they have demolished but not started construction. \r\n\t· They are interested to hear from Nick Goodman re Asda Local (I have put Nick in touch). \r\n\t· I suggested selling some of their GF commercial interests in order to raise cash - may be an angle here depending on location / asset quality. \r\n\t· Looking to exit historic and poor performing PBSA kit (Sheffield and Droylesdon are a couple of the assets). Very poor assets with occupancy lower than 50-60%.\r\n\t· They have a vacant workspace in Stratford (opposite the station) – tenant / operator needs to be an affordable workspace to tie in with S106. \r\n \r\nShare Price and Recent Press\r\nhttps://www.constructionnews.co.uk/sections/contractors/watkin-jones-ceo-departs-as-firm-flags-45m-exceptional-costs-19-07-2023/\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Tris Ford,tristram.ford@watkinjones.com,\n26e328d4-4750-4e61-8ba8-e6c99d133d7a,Waypoint Asset Management,,Institutional,8011649c-48e3-44db-9fff-c3023f2e7612,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.936468,2026-03-12 09:42:25.936468,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"13/07/2023:  Money behind them is Willis Towers Watson and Schroders. Local retail fund - Schroders [TBD], Waypoint Essential Stores (retail Parks) - Willis Towers Watson [TBD]. May have more money for retail with convenience / food store in the future. Covered by Lee Randle unless off market. Buying retail parks - bought in Barrow and bought Bodmin off market from Orchard St. £5-15m lot sizee for retail parks. High street / convenience stuff more £5-10m. Unlikely to be acquisitive on Govt Income Fund due to gilts uncertainty at present. Kristyn going on maternity leave. On a few occasions on retail parks they have been under bidder to Realty Income. Realty haven’t performed so they have picked up. \r\n\r\nValue Add shopping centres\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Kirstyn Rutter,kirstyn@waypointam.co.uk,\ncc107552-6624-4f03-a5b0-ccec77a478d6,Westminster Council,,Institutional,7c0176a4-f390-42eb-b8e8-272f0a546031,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.945322,2026-03-12 09:42:25.945322,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Sarah Jane,ssteer@westminster.gov.uk,\na1334cc6-9c72-49c6-8473-698299f7717b,Weybourne (Dyson),,Institutional,b7cea804-93ee-4527-9eac-898739351da7,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.951711,2026-03-12 09:42:25.951711,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,Min  £1 m - Cen London offices ideally,,,Mar 2026,,,,Gareth Herrington,gareth.herrington@weybourne.co.uk,\ned674444-9fef-4f97-a2ca-2872d1add4ae,Wrenbrige,,Institutional,7fdf4d7b-23e1-4bb1-a3de-3b563b86b425,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.95763,2026-03-12 09:42:25.95763,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,James Feltham,james.Feltham@wrenbridge.co.uk,\n44f528fb-05da-49b5-bd2f-fa2349510b24,Yousef Islam Foundation,,Institutional,1b2ebce2-d3be-4aa7-81c9-497d6d41ef11,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.963952,2026-03-12 09:42:25.963952,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,Up to £7m,,,Mar 2026,,,,Zafar Ashraf,zafar@yif.org.uk,\n920c39a9-ec07-4ffb-8756-ecc5ca28b716,Ares,,Institutional,c53b5eb7-2973-4e09-b364-7cabbe38c581,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.14679,2026-03-12 09:42:25.14679,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Ares have two /three vehicles \r\n•\tFlagship – opportunistic fund – IRR driven multiple test – 18%+, 1.6 EM levered true net return back to ares post fees /tax. Zero restrictions on leverage and (Come in at any stage of the development cycle). Normally low 20’s but given product could be closer to collar.\r\n•\tValue add/core +- 12-15% IRR , 1.5 EM, Levered net return discretionary to Europe – quarterly distribution of 5%.  Restricted up to 60% and can only step in after the development a forward fund wouldn’t work and a grey area for a forward purchase. Sector agnostic.\r\n•\tUS Core capital – allocation for Europe – high single digit returns net returns back to US , harder as lots of FX and fees to get it back.  \r\n•Apply equal weighting to IRR and EM. \r\n\r\n•\tAres have capital to invest – from stretch senior through to opportunistic.\r\n•\tReal estate core + / value add product – require low double digit IRRs on equity side.\r\n•\tHistorical opportunistic private equity real estate fund – requires 15% IRR and ‘can do anything’.\r\n•\t£1bn equity in each pot, therefore £4bn equity to invest, and would use debt on this.\r\n•\tA lot of capital to deploy\r\n•\tInterested in:\r\no\tResi, logistics / industrial, light industrial, retirement living, PBSA\r\no\tSpent a good amount of time looking at retirement living but never been able to piece together\r\n•\tLike the rental angle, but is unsubstantiated with the premium people might / might not pay\r\n•\tCost of dev hard to stack up atm due to cost of dev finance\r\n•\tLast 3-4 months, seen a lot of less 'in vogue' sectors where people need to plug gap (i.e. funding gap)\r\no\tWe can provide capital to plug this\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Will Twemlow,wtwemlow@aresmgmt.com,\nc311d256-34a3-44a9-b6c0-f53877cfaac8,Bywater,,Institutional,3c728fd3-208f-487d-90cd-fcdb8d75f15e,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.21047,2026-03-12 09:42:25.21047,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Jeff McKenzie,Patrick@bywaterproperties.com,\n11c27012-0153-4d11-8397-8a5e27db2737,Cerberus,,Institutional,86337b6b-ff18-4bdc-a1f2-a1fefe67c1be,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.232418,2026-03-12 09:42:25.232418,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Steven Clegg and Lorenzo Martinengo, both MDs in the European Real Estate Team.\r\n\r\n•\tCerberus operates across credit, private equity and real estate platforms\r\n•\tTheir real estate invests in debt and equity and has invested a total of $29bn to date\r\n•\tCerberus’ residential focus covers Europe and the UK\r\n•\tSpecifically interested in UK PBSA and UK Senior Living\r\n•\tThey have recently considered backing a UK PRS platform\r\n•\tThey have also looked at shared ownership but nothing has materialised yet\r\n•\tKey questions from our initial call focussed around:\r\no\tExisting debt on the portfolio\r\no\tHow the seed portfolio has been funded\r\no\tHow AHH is taking cash out of the platform\r\no\tThe level of amenities provided at the schemes\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Lorenzo Martinengo,lmartinengo@cerberusuk.com,\n18c4fc9d-6dce-4ec4-ba55-7a4b11b31fbd,Cohabs,,Institutional,6bc6a8c8-030a-4497-8786-d822e221da6b,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.254078,2026-03-12 09:42:25.254078,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"July 2023 (React News): Co-Living platform funded by Ivanhoe Cambridge. 2,000 units in NY, Paris, Brussels. Now looking at London. Focusing largely across zones one and two in London, with an emphasis on schemes of below 100 bedrooms, and a sole focus on refurbishment of existing buildings rather than development projects. \r\n\r\n•     Existing buildings of 3,000 - 10,000 sqft \r\n•     Zones 1 - 2 London.  Preferred boroughs of Southwark, Lambeth, Wandsworth, Hammersmith & Fulham, Camden, Islington, Hackney and Tower Hamlets \r\n•     Ability to undertake extensive renovations: maximise unit layout on floor-plan, add amenity spaces, rear and loft extensions. \r\n•     Freehold \r\n•     Fast approval process with 100% cash purchase \r\n•     The opportunity must have planning for either:   \r\no     C4 (large HMO) or Sui Generis HMO buildings of 15+ existing bedrooms (can be shared bathrooms or self-contained) \r\no     C3 residential blocks of 4+ flats, not located in an Article 4 area.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Justin Shee,justin@cohabs.com,\n9a5392e9-ce45-4b09-a331-857af1d3f74e,Estama,,Institutional,499934c0-2342-40b2-ad72-a8589480b4d6,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.426039,2026-03-12 09:42:25.426039,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Nov 24:\r\nSaw Ross earlier:\r\n\r\n•\tMain mandates continue to be with Signal Capital and MDSR (Israeli money).\r\no\tLooking to bid on Festival Place, Basingstoke with MDSR. There appears to be good interest in this.\r\no\tMDSR want big >£75-100m stock and are mandated by CBRE, so will be hard to get into them.\r\n•\tDavid Roberts (old Edinburgh House) mandate continuing to look at high street and shopping centres (£4-£12m / double digit yields).\r\no\tRecently bid on something in Southsea which they liked.\r\no\tAlso bid on something in Taverstock.\r\n•\tFocus fund (owns Glenrothes and Wrexham) – considering exit strategy but C&W aware.\r\n•\tOther stock:\r\no\tBeaumont Shopping Centre, Leicester – seem to think this won’t sell.\r\no\tWorkington – Evolve buying / have bought.\r\n•\tGenerally struggling to compete with the likes of Evolve on pricing.\r\n\r\nJuly 23\r\n •\tEstama have around 7-10 staff – have a sister company that operates in Germany (property brokerage).\r\n•\tHave a JV with Signal Capital, as well as a couple of other JV partners. \r\n•\tWill look at high street and SCs in good, supply constrained towns. Likely to be more secondary. Own stuff in Taunton, Caerphilly. Not anything in London. \r\n•\tWon’t buy retail warehousing, or in towns where there is a high provision of retail (in-town or out of town).\r\n•\tFor their own money, target lot sizes are around £2-5m. Anything over will need a JV partner. \r\n•\tRecently bid on something up to £80m with JV partner. Underbidder on Livingstone SC (£55m). \r\n•\tBought Thamesgate in Gravesend last year: https://reactnews.com/article/signal-completes-thamesgate-shopping-centre-deal/\r\n•\tSold out of most their old Edinburgh House stock.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Ross Campbell,,\n94b1c3b4-4a07-4e65-8191-906a362b271f,Fiera,,Institutional,e93acb8b-b8a8-416d-a348-e361fb078ab8,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.460517,2026-03-12 09:42:25.460517,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"His main mandate at the moment is on behalf of an Israeli source. \r\n•\tSeeking double digit IRRs across resi, industrial and offices.\r\n•\tInterested in soon to be or recently PC’d industrial and taking on leasing risk – I have contacted an old developer client from KF to see if there is any angle here on their scheme in Braintree:\r\no\thttps://www.horizon120.com/\r\n•\tHave looked at vacant Central London stock (although as we know their previous attempt failed IC).\r\n•\tMore likely to do gritty standing stock where there might be an opportunity to unlock development / refurb.\r\n\r\nNick also looks for deals on behalf of Fiera’s long income funds, although they aren’t up to much at present.\r\n\r\nSeparately, Fiera also have their value add fund and logistics development fund. This is primarily in place to support their prop co’s like Package Living, Wrenbridge, Angle Property etc.\r\n\r\nFiera’s debt team have x2 pools of capital – Middle Eastern and Fiera balance sheet. They are busy but the lending market is very competitive. They are hopefully going to do their first deal from Fiera’s balance sheet soon.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Paddy Freestone,patrick.freestone@fierarealestate.com,\n6a52cde2-20ad-4260-b139-e7d17debc846,Frogmore,,Institutional,47dad2a7-c182-4213-9b16-504adff414cd,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.481985,2026-03-12 09:42:25.481985,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,,,,Mar 2026,,,,Patrick Smith,patricksmith@Frogmore.co.uk,\ncf3676c9-054b-4a84-97fb-207d6cf16ff3,Glenstone,,Institutional,93ecc077-8f64-4a2c-8d12-7cf1491f744e,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.492026,2026-03-12 09:42:25.492026,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Nick and I saw Sam Russell from Glenstone this morning.\r\n\r\n•\tGlenstone recently merged with a prop co as part of capital gains tax strategy – most of the stock likely to be sold via auction (if sold).\r\n•\tAlso own Alternative Income REIT - buying the Virgin Active, Streatham.\r\no\tOwns a lot of Travelodges.\r\n•\tGenerally, sounds like they are willing to buy anything that is a good deal.\r\n•\tTheir portfolio has a low leverage around 20% gearing. Have a facility with Handelsbanken and Lloyds and can draw down straight away.\r\n•\tSweet spot is £2-3m, but can go up to £5m for the right thing.\r\no\tDon't need IC sub £3m.\r\n•\tNeeds to be quite high-yielding.\r\n•\tThey don't like to get their hands too dirty on AM / value-add.\r\n•\tSelling a shed in Leeds at a keen yield as it has a high reversion. Incoming purchaser to take on rent review ageing building risk.\r\n•\tInterested in buying kit in Central London at low cap vals.\r\n•\tLike retail parks but becoming expensive.\r\n•\tTrack record in buying pubs – bid on the Franco Manca block in the City (bid end of last year).\r\no\tKeen to see more.\r\no\tOwn some Stonegate kit.\r\n•\t@Nick Halley to send Pizza Express, Lavender Hill and Plymleigh House, Plymouth.\r\n•\t@Jack Barratt – do you know what happened to the Revs in Cardiff? Might be worth an intro if still available.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Sam Russell,sr@glenstoneproperty.co.uk,\nae57fa31-8b9d-4945-b79b-74ee14ccd345,HOOPP,,Institutional,0796954d-670c-4d0a-867a-310db93cf715,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.538732,2026-03-12 09:42:25.538732,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"28/03/2023:  \r\nEric has been at HOOPP 2 years\r\nFocuses on industrial, offices, retail, resi (BTR and PBSA)\r\nHalf of their book is in Canada, 12% is in Europe, target for Europe will be no more than 10-15% of their book approximately 85% direct holdings, 15% indirect (funds)\r\nWill take development risk – have a $4bn development pipeline\r\nartners include Tishman Speyer, Invesco, Greystar and The Crown Estate one of their projects was 1 Eagle Place, so they will likely want to open an office here. They have a team of 18 investment professionals\r\nand want to open a London office next year\r\n\r\nDislikes:\r\nUninterested in seniors due to potential reputational risk and havent spent a lot of time looking at co-living. Won’t take planning risk as they ‘can’t speculate’ won’t get involved in things like proptech.\r\n\r\n31/05/2022: 15% of portfolio in Europe of which 85% direct (JVs mostly), 15% funds. \r\nTarget 10 to 12% returns but can do deals either side. Overall 30% leverage across books, typically 50% on a deal. Min 5% equity, ideally more up to 50:50. \r\nFocus on growing industrial into strategies not covered by Veridion (Big box, UK, Sweden, Denmark, Germany). 80% of european book is logistics. \r\nBack Greystar and Invesco for resi, likely more Greystar going forward. Including UK, Spain, Ireland, Netherlands. Prefer to back operators/developers. \r\nOpen to London offices but no primary focus. Prefers programmatic, tied to existing partners unless opportunity is compelling. Looking to open London office 2023. Current office partners are Crown Estate and Helical. Mentioned global relationship with Tristan (funds/coinvest), and with AXA for developments.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Eric Piesman,eplesman@hoopp.com,\n100a343f-ee92-48ac-b3ee-a4a3cb8b2df3,ICG,,Institutional,8a01431a-a95c-4fae-b262-9a1c301f4e83,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.545276,2026-03-12 09:42:25.545276,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"09/01/2023: •\tICG Longbow - historically UK debt\r\n•\tLaunched sale and lease back fund and now raising value add/opportunistic fund\r\n•\tc.$7bn AUM on the real estate side\r\n•\tJust under $70bn AUM overall\r\n\r\n•\tFirst fund (Real Estate Lending)\r\n•\tSecond fund (Sale and Leaseback)\r\n•\tThird fund (Value Add/Opportunistic)\r\n•\tTarget IRR 15%\r\n•\tDeploying balance sheet capital and raising new Value Add/Opportunistic fund\r\n\r\n•\tPan European - UK, France, Germany\r\n•\tPreviously invested in a lot of logistics, taking advantage of reduced pricing, acquired c. £400m of assets\r\n•\tResi is another key focus but not stabilised BTR\r\n•\tResi development for sale and rent, expecting softening in yields\r\n•\tTarget IRR 15%+\r\n•\tKeen to develop platform within their business and want to expand on residential\r\n•\tLimited capacity before Christmas as they have two live deals ongoing\r\n\r\nICG formulated an offer for Edmonton in 2018. \r\n21/09/22 - Historically core plus investors in their first fund. Their first fund invested in S&L assets - mission critical assets. From residential in the Baltics to logistics in the UK, and supermarkets in Europe. Done well historically through their credit background – can get comfortable on tenants where others may not. Deals include Jaguar Land Rover campus and Royal Mail, Edinburgh. Struggle with offices and high street retail. \r\nNew opportunistic capital with new fund raise. Being more thematic (logistics and light industrial). Looking at food retail vehicle and niche mission critical assets (eg Wembley Arena). Target returns of double digit IRRS / stabilised cash on cash of 5-7%\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Chad Brown,chad.brown@icgam.com,\nc7cce924-3d78-4b53-93a5-36fdc9b7194e,KF-IM,,Institutional,fd347546-5f7d-4034-9df7-307421a066ad,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.597065,2026-03-12 09:42:25.597065,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"•\tHarry works across transactions and fund / asset mngt\r\n•\tWorks on the Lancashire PF. Target c.£10m lot sizes. Product needs to be located in Lancashire. Not much money to spend atm. 13 assets in the portfolio. \r\n•\tAlso works on one of KFIM’s pooled PF mandates (capital from Lancashire CC PF, Berkshire CC PF and a London LA PF). UK-wide mandate. £20-30m target lot size. Will do forward fundings. Buying Lidl and McDonalds atm [TBD if it was for this mandate], and another high street block. Money to spend but unlikely to be retail, perhaps sheds / alternatives. Will be buying in Q4. \r\n•\tMiddle Eastern mandate - opportunistic buyer. Harry referenced this mandate as ‘bottom feeders’. Wants value-add offices. Recently bought an office in the West End. Also bought in St Albans and Edinburgh. Looking for distress.\r\n•\tNew, separate mandate with Berkshire CC PF following the success of Lancs CC PF. Product has to be in Berkshire. Have money to spend. Circa £2-10m lots. \r\n•\tLong income fund has some sales coming. \r\n•\tDiscussed AM fees - their mandates work off income and asset value. Depends on how the fund is set up. Thinks charging AM fees off income better, although referenced this was not the case during Covid as no rent was collected. \r\n•\tDiscussed Biggin Hill – Bombardier credit won’t be good enough for their long-income fund, but asked to have a look to see if they can find another home for it.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Ollie Donaldson,Oliver.Donaldson@KF-IM.com,\nd51ea85e-e183-4e10-bee1-042c74ccccac,Sculptor,,Institutional,e3114fd9-7380-48a5-9443-7d0e6e88e99a,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.814247,2026-03-12 09:42:25.814247,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Like alternatives, in particular living sectors. Search for scalable opportunities.\r\n2/12 TS: Doing debt deals, not sure on Equity\r\nTarget sectors are European and UK healthcare/senior living and hotels, and UK retail, although they will invest over a wide range of asset classes. Sweet spot £50-100m but can go larger, £15-20m min. $1bn to deploy over the next few years, with their primary capital targeting mid-teens return.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Will Dear,will.dear@sculptor.com,\na6bb063e-9de3-4144-a6b0-69051d6ec30e,LaSalle Investment Management,,Institutional,30c55db8-2775-4674-a257-3dc12ba769be,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.612624,2026-03-12 09:42:25.612624,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Aug 23 - They are selling their Premier Inn in Richmond from their Total Pension Fund. Under offer to CBREIM. Lot size around £11m. Has been under offer for 18 months due to cladding issues. Costs to rectify cladding issues factored into CBREIM offer and novated to them so that LaSalle have a clean exit. \r\n\r\nSelling Tortilla and one other shop in Reading to KFIM (for their Berkshire PF). WAULT approx. 10 years. Sam Waterworth acting for KFIM. \r\n\r\nBuying a PBSA scheme in Lincoln (CBRE acting for them). Long income play to the uni. \r\n\r\nGenerally focussed on long income (>15 year income with RPI uplifts). \r\n\r\nLooked at Biggin but put off by the metrics. \r\n\r\nHave value add money looking at living sectors, life sciences and sheds. \r\n\r\nTotal and Santander PF (that Chris works on) unlikely to be doing much. Generally pension funds are struggling to meet redemptions and the lack of liquidity in property is causing them issues. Therefore they are more likely to look at bonds, equities etc. The same will be true across all other UK PFs, who will continue to be net sellers.\r\n\r\nThey have seen Debenhams in Oxford. They aren’t looking at it as they are developing the old Boswell Book shop with Reef (opposite the Debs).\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Chris House,chris.house@lasalle.com,\nd68e1709-54c6-4d83-bff3-a96ff2141b48,Longmead,,Institutional,40d8fadd-1b74-49ea-ba0e-cec56685f2c6,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.633347,2026-03-12 09:42:25.633347,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Longmead Capital: Overview and Investment Profile\r\nWho They Are: Longmead Capital is an independent investment manager specializing in UK real estate and infrastructure investments. Founded in 2014, the firm operates with a proactive and research-driven approach, managing funds on behalf of family offices, high-net-worth individuals, and institutional investors. The team has extensive experience in direct real estate and sale-and-leaseback agreements, with a notable deal history including transactions in sectors such as car parks and logistics.\r\n\r\nActive Requirements and Interests:\r\n1.\tCar Park Portfolios:\r\no\tLongmead owns a large Q-Park portfolio and is familiar with market dynamics, including portfolios previously brought to market.\r\no\tInterested in single-let car parks, particularly those with alternative use potential.\r\n2.\tOffice Properties:\r\no\tInterest in offices with narrow floor plates, as these tend to provide flexibility for single-let use or specific tenants.\r\no\tThey find multi-let office buildings with larger floor plates more challenging.\r\n3.\tOpen Storage:\r\no\tTend to lease open storage to tenants.\r\no\tPension fund money backs this strategy so needs income return.\r\n4.\tCorporate M&A:\r\no\tActively seeking M&A opportunities in the logistics and haulage sectors, including businesses like Eddie Stobart or port-related companies.\r\n5.\tGeneral Approach:\r\no\tMay engage agents for acquisitions but also comfortable pursuing direct deals.\r\n\r\nSources of Capital: Longmead’s capital comes from a diversified pool, including:\r\n•\tFamily offices\r\n•\tHigh-net-worth individuals\r\n•\tInstitutional investors\r\n\r\nTheir investment capacity and strategy align with conservative underwriting and risk-adjusted returns.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Alex Tollett,alex.tollett@longmeadcapital.com,\n6515ba7f-0f6a-41f6-a822-d896eab214a9,Mubadala,,Institutional,25d6166a-eb77-4561-a3bf-3f0fbc6c46f3,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.700277,2026-03-12 09:42:25.700277,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Mubadala are seeking 50:50 JVs.\r\nUK partner is Delancey\r\n\r\n1.\tUAE Sovereign Wealth Fund based in Abu Dhabi\r\n2.\t$243bn AUM\r\n3.\tIRR driven, flex hold period 3-5 yrs\r\n4.\tNeed to be a 50:50 (or 45:45:10) investor with additional capital/operating partner\r\n5.\tOperator needs track record and boots on ground\r\n6.\tRequire governance rights \r\n7.\tHave Seniors/Care: EU platform (Spain and Portugal) long leases indexed to CPI, let to ORPEA – higher care/nursing\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Richard Nordell,Rnordell@mubadala.ae,\n0ed1bc84-8796-4826-822a-861a4fa1c693,Native Land,,Institutional,edf59bc7-a809-4c0e-a853-e14f28d5f4c4,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.706675,2026-03-12 09:42:25.706675,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Aug 23 - Bid on 125 Shaftesbury and The Place, Holborn. Bids on 125 next week. Rumours Mike Hussey (Almacanter).\r\n \r\nLooked at SCs for full scale repurpose with redo focus. \r\n \r\nTargeting ground up dev Z1 and 2 for Singaporean fund. Also targeting Z1 office refurb.\r\n \r\nTargeting gateway SE cities for resi development with family office money (Gford, Oxford a Cambridge. Also currently building in Edinburgh).\r\n \r\nStruggling on the capital raise for Guildford. Likely to build to podium level and refinance. \r\n \r\nUse contractors including McAlpine, Osborne. \r\n \r\nJV with Derwent on site next to KF offices. Native Land developing the resi for sale. \r\n \r\nThey looked at Debs Oxford (send). Also send V-A London Tracker. Horse ferry Burberry. Great Queen Street.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Finn Carew,,\nc7266db8-d75b-491d-aa67-d6dbfaf903c1,Newcore,,Institutional,2678846f-8aa2-47ac-a290-94269c256387,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.713339,2026-03-12 09:42:25.713339,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"July 2023 (React News): Newcore Capital has acquired seven assets for its £190m Newcore Special Situations V (NSS V) fund, including properties in several new subsectors. The acquisitions total £25m and are spread across Greater London and neighbouring commuter towns. The purchases include 2 petrol stations with EV charging in Crouch End and Streatham, and a mortuary in Surrey let to Dignity Funerals. This is the first time Newcore has invested in the roadside and funeral care sectors, driven by increasing demand for EV charging and the UK’s ageing population. As part of its latest round of acquisitions, Newcore has also purchased nurseries in Whitton, Beaconsfield and Clapham, and a special needs school in Horsham.\r\n\r\nNSS V reached its final close in May after securing £190m in equity commitments. Investors include Merseyside and Clwyd local government pension schemes, two European fund-of-funds managers, insurance and corporate pension schemes, family offices and high-net-worth individuals. Newcore is aiming to deploy £350m over the next two years for NSS V, with target asset classes including education, healthcare, storage, life sciences and transport. Lot sizes are targeted between £2m and £25m.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Harry Smart,harry.smart@newcorecapital.com,\n12fd1641-7717-4234-9dba-b588fa5acd6b,Pinebridge Benson Elliot,,Institutional,8a2d0b28-9b47-465f-82dd-850f59587b11,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.767402,2026-03-12 09:42:25.767402,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Owns Sigma, regional housebuilder. Looking for platform plays.\r\nPineBridge Screening Call 30/01/2023\r\n\r\nSummary\r\n•\tOpportunistic cost of capital 15%+, more like 20%+\r\n•\t3-5 year hold\r\n•\t1.5x MM\r\n•\tFund 5 closed EUR850\r\n•\tLooking at providing funding gap finance\r\n•\tKeen to deploy for mid to high teens \r\n•\tAre not a debt fund\r\n•\tWe have done one seniors deal in UK, which has fallen out of planning 2019 - Audley model\r\n•\tWe have a retirement rental strategy in Spain - development\r\n•\tOwn Sigma capital single family home delivery platform and looking at more BTR\r\n•\tSigma have 5,000 units under management. Scope to leverage that brand into BTR. We won't be sharpest pricing.\r\n•\t£20m plus ticket size, can go smaller for programmatic \r\n•\tBeds and sheds focus\r\n•\tCautious on offices, retail is a no\r\n•\tHistorically done a lot of hotels but not very active recently\",,,Mar 2026,,,,George MacKinnon,George.MacKinnon@pinebridge.com,\n1098151e-2967-4bbe-9ea1-276bca7edf79,Tellon Capital,,Institutional,871d2efd-cfa0-4150-b734-7a3e9923f3fb,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.870891,2026-03-12 09:42:25.870891,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"Central London, Greater London & South East Offices\r\n• Freehold & Long Leasehold (Max 7 0% rents receivable gearing and in excess of 7 05 years unexpired)\r\n• Max 7 0 min walk to underground or mainline rail station\r\n• £10m - £150m\r\n• Short income to vacant possession or vacant possession\r\n• Ability to refurbish or redevelop with or without planning\r\n\r\nIndustrial\r\n• Freehold & Long Leasehold (Max 7 0% rents receivable gearing and in excess of 7 05 years unexpired)\r\n• South of M6 and East of the M5\r\n• £2m - £70m\r\n• 30,000 sq ft - 100,000 sq ft\r\n• Short income to vacant possession or vacant possession\r\n• Ability to refurbish or redevelop with or without planning\r\n\r\nPrime Retail\r\n• Freehold & Long Leasehold (Max 7 0% rents receivable gearing and in excess of 105 years unexpired)\r\n• Prime retail towns and cities with good quality connections\r\n• South of Birmingham, as far west as Bristol and as far east as Chelmsford, Central London excluded\r\n• £1 m - £70m\r\n• Vacant possession, part vacant or leases with 7 8 months or less unexpired\r\n\r\n•\tThey are continuing to look for value add offices in London. They recently looked at the Matalan on Oxford St and M&S [TBD Oxford St or Tottenham Court Rd]. \r\n•\tLooking at Debenhams in Oxford, although require floor to ceiling height of 3 metres.\r\n•\tThey have a resi scheme in Southampton (Bargate Qtr) that was being forward funded by L&G. Henry's were the contractor who have gone bust, so they are re-tendering for this. \r\n•\tBought and developed 16 Eastcheap with their Wealth Preservation fund. Unlikely to be acquisitive from this. Rupert and Lucy do the leasing on this. \r\n•\tMost of their money comes from 12 or so family offices (assumed to be mostly from Israel). Main source is Ben Hamburger (Founding Partner), who is former CEO of Harel (Israel’s largest insurance group). \r\n•\tAppetite to buy in London or cities with a good story. Need development / refurb angle and short hold to generate high IRRs to investors.  \r\nWill also buy LH assets.\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Evan Sawyer,evans@telloncapital.com,\n9913978c-b52c-44a9-8ff4-523807855f11,Varde,,Institutional,c6343c4a-d46e-47f1-b688-53747e2e6c84,,,,,2026-03-12 09:42:25.924215,2026-03-12 09:42:25.924215,f,f,f,f,f,Active,,,,,\"2025/02/28\r\n\r\nWe’re not buying anything at the moment – focus is very much on credit (lending). Very happy to support any processes that you’re running or provide financing terms to support an acquisition (but deals need to be £100m+ ideally).\r\n\r\n2023/05/26\r\n\r\nGary Roberts / Senior Advisor / groberts.advisor@varde.com/ +44 7787 550 847\r\n\t· 20 year career\r\n\t· Capital advisors at CBRE - 8/9 years \r\n\t· Left in 2014 and 9 years COO of Praxis real estate focussing on opportunistic opportunities \r\n\t· 2 weeks ago joined the Varde team - for UK and Ireland\r\n \r\nVarde history\r\n\t· Historically PE and looking for distress \r\n\t· Haven't done anything in UK/ Europe since 2018/2019\r\n\t· Inactive in the UK over the last few years have made a commercial lending book in the US\r\n\t· Bought Bizspace and bought with Crest Nicholson, which apparently did well\r\n \r\nVarde now\r\n\t· Aim is to be a Capital solutions provider back sponsors and assets - not looking for distress \r\n\t· Half a billion in the market in the next 12 months \r\n\t· In the UK they think immediate opportunities will be lending  - gap funding / loan acquisitions \r\n\t· Next phases is equity. They have the capital there if its right \r\n\t· Returns need to be attractive \r\n\t· Location agnostic\r\n\t· Sector agnostic - mentioned retail warehousing/ offices / self storage/ PBSA\r\n\t· Has doubts on shopping centres. Anything with department store vacancy is a challenge \r\n\t· Nothing is an immediate no \r\n\t· Mentioned the retail schemes in Yates and Luton being good deals\r\n\t· Varde have presence in Scandanavia / Southern Europe / UK and Ireland -  other locations also covered  within Varde  \r\n\t· Primary strategy without planning is a no \r\n\t· Run two funds - very happy to go to 70% half paid half accrued \r\n\t· Returns / Metrics \r\n\t\t\to Mid-teens IRRs\r\n\t\t\to 70% debt loan / high single figure 8/9% deals\r\n\t\t\to Preferred equity and structured equity can be done\r\n\t\t\to Common equity needs to be 20+%\r\n\t\t\to Ticket size north of £25m min - programmatic is challenging without sizeable deployment\",,,Mar 2026,,,,Gary Robers,groberts.advisor@varde.com/,\n"